      "title": "Ḥāl (الحال)",
      "titleArabic": "الحال",
      "content": [
        "Ḥāl (adverb of manner/state) describes the condition of the subject or object at the time of the action. It is always in the accusative case and usually indefinite."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Describes state during the action",
        "Always manṣūb and usually indefinite",
        "Can be a single word, phrase, or sentence",
        "Agreement in number and gender with ṣāḥib al-ḥāl"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "جَاءَ الطَّالِبُ مُسْرِعًا", "english": "The student came hurrying" },
        { "arabic": "رَأَيْتُهَا جَالِسَةً", "english": "I saw her sitting" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Exclamatory Forms (أسلوب التعجب)",
      "titleArabic": "أسلوب التعجب",
      "content": [
        "Arabic has two main patterns for expressing wonder or exclamation: مَا أَفْعَلَ and أَفْعِلْ بِـ. Both express amazement at a quality."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Pattern 1: مَا أَفْعَلَ + object",
        "Pattern 2: أَفْعِلْ بِـ + prepositional phrase",
        "Both express 'How [adjective] is X!'",
        "Derived from Form I triliteral verbs"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "مَا أَجْمَلَ السَّمَاءَ!", "english": "How beautiful the sky is!" },
        { "arabic": "أَجْمِلْ بِهِ!", "english": "How beautiful it/he is!" },
        { "arabic": "مَا أَعْظَمَ هَذَا الْكِتَابَ!", "english": "How great this book is!" }
      ]
    }
